SIMPLE: solvent
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Solvent
<hw>Sol"vent</hw> <pr>(s⟦ocr⟧l"v⟦eit⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>solvens</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>solvere</ets>. See
<er>Solvable</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the power of
dissolving; dissolving; <as>as, a <ex>solvent</ex> fluid</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>solvent</xex> body.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Able or sufficient to pay all just debts; <as>as, a
<ex>solvent</ex> merchant; the estate is
<ex>solvent</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Solvent</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Solvent
<hw>Sol"vent</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A substance
(usually liquid) suitable for, or employed in, solution, or in
dissolving something; <as>as, water is the appropriate <ex>solvent</ex>
of most salts, alcohol of resins, ether of fats, and mercury or acids of
metals, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which resolves; <as>as, a <ex>solvent</ex> of
mystery</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Solver</ent>⟦br⟧
